The paper deals with error control in communication scenarios, which is a topic that falls under the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The models introduced in the paper involve queuing systems and registers, which are data structures that are commonly studied in the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also discusses variations of the models, which may involve algorithms and complexity analysis, making it relevant to the distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The models are motivated by timing channels and bit-shift channels, which are examples of signal processing and machine learning (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of zero-error capacity, which is a topic that falls under the network information theory (cs.NI) sub-category.
